description.text: I decided to make another wood block similar to my first project for my friend because she liked it a lot.  The corner designs are the same but everything else is slightly different.  After printing, I had to go over the words and heart in brown permanent marker so that they would stand out from everything else.

Making this wood block is really easy.  Simply create a design in Illustrator or other sketch program.  Measure the height and width so that and do some quick math to make sure the design will start on the correct place on the block.  Because I couldn't find a heart design I liked, I drew my own heart, scanned it into Photoshop and make some slight adjustments.  The printing settings on the Epilog Engraver are 50/100.  Lastly, any part of the design you want to stand out should be traced in a dark permanent marker.

description.text:
Taylor Swift says Speak Now!  The design of the plaque revolves around the quote by Taylor Swift said around the world on her Speak Now tour.  I made this for my sister because she is a big fan of Taylor and wanted to remember her memorable words.  I printed the design on black acrylic by using the CNC laser printer. I chose black acrylic in order for the letters and design to be more legible to read and stand out.  The design was created in Illustrator.  Hopefully my sister will like the plaque I made for her. 
Quote: Real life is a funny thing you know. I think most of us feel like weâ€™re reaching the end of our lives and looking back and regretting moments when we didnâ€™t speak up, when we didnâ€™t say â€œI love you!â€ When we shouldâ€™ve said â€œIâ€™m Sorry!â€ So thereâ€™s a time for silence, thereâ€™s a time to wait your turn.  But if you so clearly know how you feel and so clearly know what you need to say youâ€™ll know it.  I donâ€™t think you should wait, I think you should Speak Now.  â€“ Taylor Swift

• Create a new document in Illustrator (10 in. by 7 in.).
  • Create a rectangle and the create another rectangle slightly smaller inside of the bigger one.
  • Make the outside rectangle .001 stroke (vector cut)
  • Inside the slightly smaller rectangle copy and paste song lyrics then balance them out by centering them.
  • Add designs to balance the lyrics out on each side of plaque.
  • Before completed center everything so everything is even and symmetrical.
  • Now the plaque is completed!

description.text: Vaccines remain one of the most important tools that can be used to improve health. However, there are millions of children each year who are not vaccinated (a great overview: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK2284/). This number is simply unacceptable. Vaccines are usually available, but issues around the supply and distribution of these vaccines limit their efficient delivery. Unfortunately, of the vaccines that are delivered, many are given to children who have already been inoculated but do not have adequate records. These children are re-inoculated to be safe, wasting the valuable resource. Organisations like VaxTrac (http://vaxtrac.com/) are working to solve some of these problems using innovative software, but in the meantime another system is needed to track vaccination. VaxBeads are 3D printed immunization records which will make it easier to determine what vaccines a child needs. Each bead represents a different vaccine. The shape and colour of each bead is unique to a specific vaccine. The beads are customized on the spot with the child's initials, date of birth, and an identifying number. If possible, this number will correspond to some form of national identification. The name of the vaccine and the date given are printed on the bead. Vaccines given in multiple doses are marked with a number that corresponds to the dose. Vaccination cards are easily lost or destroyed, and their value is often difficult to convey. VaxBeads are more durable than a vaccination card, and the customized object will hopefully seem more valuable than a slip of paper. It is also easier and quicker to read than a vaccination card, especially when multiple cards have been used for one child. This tool allows health care workers to quickly assess which vaccines a child has and which vaccines a child needs. It also gives parents a simple tool to ensure that their child has the necessary vaccines. A sample poster for parents is shown above. The beads could be worn as a bracelet or necklace on days when vaccinations are given, and stored at other times. A similar concept would be to 3D print pieces of a watchband. When the watchband is completed, the child would be given a watch to wear with the band. The VaxBeads could be used as part of a program to promote vaccination. A completed set of beads, with the patient information matching, could be shown to an organization in exchange for goods or money. This would essential reimburse the parents for any expenses or troubles they took to get the child the proper vaccinations. This incentive would give more motivation for people to actively seek vaccines their child is missing. Most importantly, a simple tool like this allows people to easily determine if their children are getting appropriate medical care. This empowers them to petition their local governments and get the care they need.

Printing of these beads should be relatively easy. The overhangs in the designed part would need to be tweaked depending on the printer. The size of the bead could also be adjusted depending on the resolution of the printer. The largest technical hurdle would be the use different coloured plastics. This would be especially problematic if multiple vaccines were given at the same time, as switching polymers takes some time and cause some material waste. Although multiple colours would allow for easier differentiation, the shape alone could also be used. As printers continue to advance, multiple colour printing should become easier to accomplish.  
The current beads represent some typical vaccines:Yellow Fever, Hib, MMR and DTP. MMR is given in two rounds, hence the MMR 1 and 2. It is easy to see that you could make all sorts of beads.   
The red cube has a smiley face on one side. This could be customized based on the child's preference. Immunizations are necessary, not fun. That is no reason to be dreary.

UPDATES!
I'm updating the Y-axis shroud and adding a specific X-axis shroud.

Y-Axis update- Removed the top two ducts on the pulley side of the stepper due to a recent home operation; the Y-carriage contacted the shroud as it attempted to home and wouldn't pass by to reach the micro switch. I also extended the side shroud to encompass the stepper allowing for a smooth side duct for additional cooling.

X-Axis. The original shroud worked for this side, but comes too close to the Rambo board enclosure as the Z-axis moved. I removed 4mm from one side which should clear the Rambo board enclosure and the mounting screw.

Extruder shroud remains unchanged.

I will include an enclosure print and photos of the temp controller soon.

Since building an enclosure for my Prusa I3 Original, the stepper motors seem to run a bit warmer than I want, so I began looking for cooling shrouds and printed a few but decided on this one originally designed by IvanFjodorovich. I liked the fit but the fan opening wasn't large enough for the fans full potential and the base was .9mm thick which required the use of through bolting and additional hardware. So I decided to add my personal touches.

X-Axis & Extruder:
I redesigned the mount to open up the fan hole to take full advantage of the 40MM fan unit, add a thicker base, eliminated the slotted mounting holes, and added stand offs to allow the mounting of the fan with the supplied screws(without additional hardware). The 4 stand offs serve two purposes by spacing the shroud to allow proper airflow, even if you push the shroud full depth on the stepper, and prevents the mounting screws from protruding when mounting the fan motor. The shrouds original design prints well and allows for a snug fit on the stepper motor, so no changes were made there.

Y-Axis.
Since the Y carriage passes over the top of the Y-axis stepper so closely, I shaved the top fins, extended the bottom and one side's fins to pull more air across those sides to compensate for the lack of cooling on the top.

Fans curtesy of Amazon (http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000VRVHFO?psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00)
and come with the mounting screws also.

Third addition to the mix was a way to control these fans. Sure I could have just wired them direct to the PSU(which means they run constantly even after an all night print - until the power was switched off), or piggy backed them to the extruder fan(but wasn't sure what the board was capable of supporting)
I chose the best solution for me. I also found these nifty 12V adjustable thermal fan switch relays with temp sensor (http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00VFD08RQ?psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00) allowing me to control the on and off temps of the fan and connecting directly to the unused 12V outputs on my PSU. This way when the temp on the stepper rises, the fan kicks on and when they cool, the fan switches off.

Happy Printing and I hope that this additional information extends the life of your machine as well.

description.text:
A slight modification to Gossamer's thing that adds sections with a narrow diameter at the bottom of the bolt head holes. This makes it less easy to install (you have to completely remove the bolts) but I think this will make it less likely to slip off the bolt heads if tension is high and helps spread the force from the bolt heads across a larger surface area preventing damage to the plywood or acrylic. In my case the bolts had already been over-tightened which lead to deformation of the plywood and cracks in the acrylic.
Note1: It might help to drill some 6mm holes in the left side panel of the printer so you can access the bolts holding the left end piece to the Y-Carriage without having to remove the Y-Rods and Y-Carriage. I made mine at the Y-Home position for easy repeatable location of the bolt heads (see picture).
Note2: A 4.4mm hole allows you to use the little clear plastic collars from the end of the ABP rollers as hole inserts with built in washers to protect the plywood from being damaged if you over-tighten the tension screw. If you do not have any of these to spare you should at least use a washer or two!

• Modify the .SCAD file changing "twice_z_resolution" to the value in mm of double that of a single layer of printed plastic.
  • Print, cleanup, insert captive nut.
  • Remove side panels/remove plywood parts/drill holes etc. so you can access the motor mount bolts and pass through the tensioner bolt (see parent file instructions for detailed help)
  • Remove the 4x M3 bolts that hold the motors in place
  • Insert printed piece and reinsert motor mount bolts, ensuring you do not tighten then too much
  • Insert a bolt through the hole you have hopefully drilled in the right place on the rear panel for Y-belt or left end piece of Y-Carriage for X-belt
  • Tighten tension bolt until you have the correct belt tension (if you want you can further tighten the motor mount bolts now)
  • Re-attach any removed printer parts
  • Print with higher speeds and better results!

description.text:
This is a modification to InMoov's Top Stomach enabling it to lean forward and back and side to side.
Print 2 each of the following parts;
TS Pistons
TS Side Pivot Sockets
TS Servo holder
TS Side PivBlk
TS Middle Plate
Print 1 each of all the rest.
Also print - TStoBackLeftV1, TStoBackRightV1 TStoFrontLeftV1,TStoFrontRightV1 from InMoov's website. If you are adapting the Top Stomach reuse these parts.

Update March 16/16 Also print, DiskUnderV1, DiskExternV2, DiskInternV3 so that the Logo plate can be attached.
Once all parts are printed, fit them and make sure they are moving freely before installing them. Grease all of the ball joints and pistons. The base does not have a race in it for ball bearings. I used a 1/4" teflon plate between this and the Mid Stomach, it works great - grease that too. This base will bolt on to the StomGearV2.

Wiring
You need 2 intact - HS-805BB servos (drive servo) and 2 - HS 805 BB servos with the boards removed or disabled, the pots and the stop removed (slave servo). Connect the motor leads from the intact servo to the motor leads of the slave servo - make sure they move in opposite directions. Do this for both the Back servo's and the Side servo's.
Set the drive servo's to 90 degrees before installing.

3/14/2016 Update; The Base Right STL originally posted has been up dated. The Base left was uploaded twice.
06/12/2017 Update; I found that the ball and socket can separate if pulled on to far or lifted. There is now a new 2 part main socket that will hold better. Bolt it together after installing and insert the pin. I hot glued the pin in place.

description.text:
This detonator switch is something Wylie Coyote would be eager to get his hands on. It can be used to activate most anything requiring a momentary switch, such as model rocket launches, sound effects, or traps designed to ensnare a pesky road runner.

The detonator switch consists of a plunger handle that, when pushed down, activates a microswitch within the base. The base also contains two integrated AA battery holders that can be used to supply power to an external circuit via the microswitch. The integrated battery holders are a remix from enif's Flexing AA battery holder with integrated spring - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:456900 (thanks again enif for a wonderful design!). The changes I made to enif's design for this application include raising the height of the "box" so that the top of the battery holder is flush with the battery.

The detonator switch box is designed to look like it was constructed of wooden planks. There are now three designs of the box available; a plain top, one with the word "BOOM!" recessed in the front, and one for my Bug B Gone design (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1449658). Feel free to remix the plain top with any message/graphic you like.

The attached PDF includes all the information needed to construct the detonator switch, including print settings I used.

description.text: An unexpected survival situation could happen to anyone, anywhere! The most critical 'bootstrap' file you need for any CNC device is this arrowhead template. Only after cutting out this variety pack of classic stick barbs will you be ready to survive, to remain alive, to live. Ancient man cut these same arrowheads, and that is why you are here today. To defend your valuable laser cutter, to overcome challenges, as a handsome decoration for your shop, and to win Lazzzor Battle 2008!

Warning: These are sharp! Cut AAROHEADS file from a durable heavyweight substrate, metal recommended. Gather assortment of straight sticks, or gather dowels from Home Depot. Prepare arrow shafts by removing bark from sticks and cutting notches in the ends. Place arrowheads in notches and wrap with cordage. Add feathers or other 'fletching' and let 'er rip. Tips:
Primitive man may have poisoned his arrows.
You can use arrowheads to peel the bark from the sticks and cut the notches, or for opening letters!

title: Halo Master Chief Helmet - Cortana A.I. Chip Receiver Port

description.text:
This model is a simple receiver box to allow you to insert a Halo UNSC A.I. Chip into the back of a Halo Master Chief helmet. This model is measured based on the dimensions of the following objects:

Chip: Halo 4 Cortana Light-Up Keychain
Helmet: 'Disguise'-branded Halo 5 'Master Chief' costume helmet, adult size

This receiver box is inserted by carving out a rectangular hole into the back of the helmet and inserting the box into it, glueing into place. You can then add a Halo A.I. chip, that you can insert or remove - a perfect, subtle addition to your Halo SPARTAN cosplay that adds a touch of realism.

The box has two hollows to allow you to glue 2 10mmx2mm neodymium magnets to the box. If you then carve out two corresponding hollows in the chip itself, using a rotary tool or Dremel, you can glue in two corresponding magnets and the chip will magnetically lock into place once inserted into the helmet.

The length of the box inside the Disguise helmet does not interfere with the room inside the helmet - it does not touch the back of the head or bulge out the internal padding.

There are two pilot holes to add decorative screws once finished, or you can leave them as-is.

Disclaimer: The terms HALO, SPARTAN, Master Chief, Cortana or UNSC are all trademarks of the Microsoft Corporation - I do not claim ownership for any of these properties.

Notes:

I printed this oriented with the outside face up, for the best finish. You will need to add supports, wither for the outside lip if printing with the face up, or the inside of the box if printing in any other orientation. At the above settings with a raft, it took 2 hours to complete.

I designed this in AutoDesk 123D Design. I made a rough block at the dimensions of the A.I. chip, then a larger box to contain it (with some excess sticking out the front). I drew a rectangular sketch using the front face as a plane of axis and measuring the outside diameter of the Helmet back disk, then rounded the edges and extruded it forward and magnetised it to the front face. I altered the dimensions of the larger box until the chip stuck out enough, then subtracted the chip from the larger box. I used the same method for the two magnet rings and holes in the outside.To finish off, I chamfered the edges and rounded the edges of the inside of the box to aid insertion.

title: SETH - 3D Printed Jointed Robot (Easy Print Slic3r Settings)

description.text:
Seth The Improved Jointed Robot.
This is a remix of the original Jointed Robot created by Shira:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:555242
I printed this awesome robot & I want to share with you guys my printing experience.
So, I created some files for easy print of Seth.
Here it is:
Normally for an easy print you need to change some Slic3r Settings.
Slic3r Settings for the entire print:
Infill 20 %, Layer Height 0,1mm or 1.2mm if you wish, Speed 40mm/s & shell thickness 1 or 2 depends on the print you make, next I'll specify which print needs 1 or 2 shell thickness.
My entire print was on Layer Height 0,1mm & Infill 20% - it's enough to add resistance to the robot.
Best print for this robot is to make Slic3r adjustments for each print.
Slic3r Settings for each print:
I've places numbers for each print.
The most delicate printed parts of this robot are the neck, arms and hands.
Layer Height for the entire print is 0.1mm & NO RAFTS - NO SUPPORTS.
If an STL File appear in Orange telling you about the object that is not manifold, leave it as it is, don't repaired it. You can print perfectly how it is.

  1. Left Arm 1: Infill 20%, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 2 (Perimeters),
    Skirt & Brim - Distance from the object 0 & Brim Width 5.
  2. . Right Arm 2: Infill 20%, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 2 (Perimeters),
    Skirt & Brim - Distance from the object 0 & Brim Width 5.
  3. Hands: Infill 20 %, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 1 (Perimeters), PLA Printing Temperature for this print 195ºC & print the STL file as it is, no skirt & brim.
  4. Left Boot 1: Infill 20%, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 3 (Perimeters), no Skirt & Brim, no Supports.
  5. Right Boot 2: Infill 20%, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 3 (Perimeters), no Skirt & Brim, no Supports.
  6. Head: Infill 20%, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 2 (Perimeters),
    Skirt & Brim Distance from the object 0 & Brim Width 6, no Supports.
  7. Hip: Infill 20%, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 3 (Perimeters),
    Skirt & Brim Distance from the object 0 & Brim Width 5, no Supports.
  8. Left & Right Ball Hip: Infill 20%, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 2 (Perimeters), no Skirt & Brim, no Supports.
  9. Left Thigh 1: Infill 20 %, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 2 (Perimeters),
    Skirt & Brim - Distance from the object 0 & Brim Width 5.
  10. Right Thigh 2: Infill 20 %, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 2 (Perimeters),
    Skirt & Brim - Distance from the object 0 & Brim Width 5.
  11. Neck & Chest: Infill 60 %, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 1 (Perimeters),
    Skirt & Brim - Distance from the object 0 & Brim Width 3.
  12. Left & Right Knees: Infill 20 %, Speed 40mm/s, Shell Thickness 2 (Perimeters),
    Skirt & Brim - Distance from the object 0 & Brim Width 8.

An elastic cord is used to secure the limbs and allow for positioning - no screws required!
The elastic cord that best fits the robot is 3mm in diameter.
Note: Be careful with the joint at the base of the neck and fingers, they often remain stuck in printing, and is difficult to get moving the joint.

What is it?

My sister bought this trinket. I thought hey that would be a fun thing to scan, texture, and print!

Software/Hardware used

Nikon D7100 w/ Sigma 18-35mm F1.8 DC HSM
Arduino (teensy 3.1)
Nikon Camera Control Pro 2 (Capture)
Adobe Bridge (Processing)
Agisoft Photoscan (Scanning)
ZBrush (Texturing)
Simplify3D (Converting STL)

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker Original

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1 - 0.2

Infill:

< 5%

Scan

I took 32 photos on an automated turntable I made. I then exported the raw .NEFs through adobe bridge with lens correction and crop. I imported those jpegs into Agisoft Photoscan. This resulted in a very clean pointcloud with some random white noise around the object (the background peeking through.) I then selected by saturation all the white points.

Detail

I imported the .obj from photoscan into ZBrush. This is where i decimated the mesh to a more reasonable size and added texture details. From ZBrush I exported the .obj again.

Final STL

I imported it into Simplify3D, and exported the stl.
